WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.940 --> 00:00:09.680
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:13.020
This is a complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:13.020 --> 00:00:17.910
In this video we will cover Virtual Routing
and Forwarding, VRF.

00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:23.880
VRF allows us to divide one physical router
into multiple virtual routers.

00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:27.279
You can think of it like VLANs for routers.

00:00:27.279 --> 00:00:33.310
VLANs divide a switch into multiple virtual
switches each with their own broadcast domain,

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:39.010
and VRF divides a router into multiple virtual
routers each with their own routing table.

00:00:39.010 --> 00:00:43.070
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:00:43.070 --> 00:00:49.530
First I will introduce the concept of VRF
and its capabilities, and then introduce VRF

00:00:49.530 --> 00:00:50.870
configuration.

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:56.370
Note that VRF configuration isn’t actually
a CCNA exam topic, but I think seeing the

00:00:56.370 --> 00:00:59.610
configurations will help you understand how
it works.

00:00:59.610 --> 00:01:05.930
Unfortunately VRF isn’t supported in Packet
Tracer, so if you want to try it in a lab

00:01:05.930 --> 00:01:11.870
you’ll need to use something like Cisco
Modeling Labs, CML, or real Cisco devices.

00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:15.230
Let’s get started.

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:19.840
The diagram at the bottom gives an idea of
how VRFs work.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:25.110
The black box in the middle represents R1,
a single physical router.

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:31.250
The blue, green, and red router icons inside
represent three virtual routers inside R1,

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:32.630
three VRFs.

00:01:32.630 --> 00:01:37.580
Let’s call them VRF1, VRF2, and VRF3.

00:01:37.580 --> 00:01:43.950
So, Virtual Routing and Forwarding is used
to divide a single router into multiple virtual

00:01:43.950 --> 00:01:45.430
routers.

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:51.030
This is similar to how VLANs are used to divide
a single switch, a LAN, into multiple virtual

00:01:51.030 --> 00:01:54.149
switches, virtual LANs.

00:01:54.149 --> 00:01:59.950
By default, all interfaces on a switch are
in the same LAN, the same broadcast domain.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:06.740
When using VLANs, we can divide that one broadcast
domain into multiple virtual broadcast domains.

00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:12.720
Similarly, by default all router interfaces
are all in the same ‘routing domain’.

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:17.440
By ‘routing domain’ I mean, by default
traffic received on one router interface can

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:21.710
be forwarded out of any other interface on
the router, if the routing table says to do

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:22.710
so.

00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:30.810
For example, without using VRF, in the diagram
below traffic received on R1’s G0/0 interface

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:35.410
can be routed to and forwarded out of R1’s
G1/2 interface.

00:02:35.410 --> 00:02:38.510
However, with VRF that won’t be possible.

00:02:38.510 --> 00:02:47.730
G0/0 is in VRF1 and G1/2 is in VRF3, so traffic
cannot be forwarded between them.

00:02:47.730 --> 00:02:49.970
How does VRF accomplish this?

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:55.269
It does this allowing a router to build separate
routing tables.

00:02:55.269 --> 00:03:00.190
Normally a router has one routing table, but
with VRF it has multiple.

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:06.599
Interfaces, specifically layer 3 interfaces,
are configured to be in a specific VRF, also

00:03:06.599 --> 00:03:09.700
known as a VRF Instance.

00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:14.360
Keep in mind that VRF does not apply to Layer
2 interfaces on a switch.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:20.049
Only router interfaces, SVIs, and routed ports
on multilayer switches can be configured in

00:03:20.049 --> 00:03:21.049
a VRF.

00:03:21.049 --> 00:03:24.170
It’s a Layer 3 concept.

00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:28.740
As I mentioned before, traffic in one VRF
cannot be forwarded out of an interface in

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:30.349
another VRF.

00:03:30.349 --> 00:03:36.049
However, as an exception VRF Leaking can be
configured to allow traffic to pass between

00:03:36.049 --> 00:03:38.099
VRFs.

00:03:38.099 --> 00:03:42.099
That is a more advanced concept though and
I won’t cover it in this video.

00:03:42.099 --> 00:03:44.950
So, what is the main purpose of VRF?

00:03:44.950 --> 00:03:51.250
Well VRF is commonly used to facilitate MPLS,
multi-protocol label switching.

00:03:51.250 --> 00:03:55.430
However, that’s actually not the kind of
VRF we are talking about here.

00:03:55.430 --> 00:04:01.569
The kind of VRF we are talking about is VRF-lite,
VRF without MPLS.

00:04:01.569 --> 00:04:08.110
So, keep in mind that when I say ‘VRF’
in this video, I’m really referring to ‘VRF-lite’.

00:04:08.110 --> 00:04:13.890
VRF is commonly used by service providers
to allow one device to carry traffic from

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:15.920
multiple customers.

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:17.290
How does it help with that?

00:04:17.290 --> 00:04:19.380
Well, there are two main points.

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:24.570
First, each customer’s traffic is isolated
from the others, because each customer connects

00:04:24.570 --> 00:04:29.790
to their own virtual router within the service
provider’s physical router.

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:35.440
In the diagram below, let’s say the blue,
green, and red devices represent three different

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:36.800
customers.

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:41.500
All customers connect to the same service
provider router, R1, but each connects to

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:45.889
a different virtual router, a different VRF
instance.

00:04:45.889 --> 00:04:50.600
And another major point is that customer IP
addresses can overlap without issues.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:05:01.770
For example, the blue customer uses subnets
192.168.1.0/24 and 192.168.2.0/24.

00:05:01.770 --> 00:05:06.160
The green customer also uses 192.168.1.0/24
and 2.0/24.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:11.130
And so does the red customer.

00:05:11.130 --> 00:05:15.630
Without VRF, this kind of configuration is
not possible on a router.

00:05:15.630 --> 00:05:19.700
But with VRF, it works fine even though the
IP addresses all overlap.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:25.570
Okay, now let’s try configuring VRF to help
understand how it works.

00:05:25.570 --> 00:05:31.020
To demonstrate VRF configuration I’ll use
the network below.

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:37.949
SPR1 is a service provider router providing
WAN services to two customers, Customer 1

00:05:37.949 --> 00:05:39.730
and Customer 2.

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:48.630
C1R1 and C1R2 belong to Customer 1 and C2R1
and C2R2 belong to customer 2.

00:05:48.630 --> 00:05:50.470
Note the subnets being used.

00:05:50.470 --> 00:05:55.460
Both Customer 1 and Customer 2 use subnet
192.168.1.0/30.

00:05:55.460 --> 00:06:03.270
First, let’s see what happens when we try
to configure this without using VRF.

00:06:03.270 --> 00:06:09.980
First I configured SPR1’s G0/0 and G0/1,
both connected to Customer 1’s routers.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:12.040
No problems yet.

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:20.570
But when I try to configure G0/2, I get an
error message, 192.168.1.0 overlaps with G0/0.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:29.130
G0/2 cannot use IP address 192.168.1.1 because
it is in the same subnet as G0/0.

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:34.150
In this case it’s the exact same IP address,
but even if the IP address is different it

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:35.220
won’t work.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:36.770
Let me demonstrate that.

00:06:36.770 --> 00:06:44.760
To prove that point I tried to configure it
as 192.168.1.2, but again it didn’t work.

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:49.880
Even if the IP address is different, G0/2
cannot be configured in the same subnet as

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:51.210
G0/0.

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:58.920
So, without the use of VRF, two interfaces
on the same router cannot be in the same subnet.

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:04.690
Next let’s use VRF to configure this network
properly.

00:07:04.690 --> 00:07:09.190
First we have to create the VRFs, which can
be done in global config mode with the command

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:13.500
IP VRF, followed by the VRF name.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:19.740
Here I created two VRFs, one named CUSTOMER1
and the other CUSTOMER2.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:25.330
I then used the command SHOW IP VRF which
shows all of the VRFs on the router.

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:28.750
As you can see, the CUSTOMER1 and CUSTOMER2
VRFs were created.

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:34.960
The next step is to assign interfaces to each
VRF.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:42.970
So, from interface config mode for G0/0 I
used the command IP VRF FORWARDING CUSTOMER1.

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:50.199
G0/0 is now part of the CUSTOMER1 VRF, however
I also got this message.

00:07:50.199 --> 00:07:57.840
Interface G0/0 IPv4 disabled and addresses
removed due to enabling VRF CUSTOMER1.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:02.850
If an interface has an IP address configured,
the IP address will be removed when you assign

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:05.230
the interface to a VRF.

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:12.210
So, I then re-configured the IP address, 192.168.1.1/30.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:14.030
I then configured G0/1.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:19.360
Again, the IP address I configured before
was removed when I assigned it to the VRF,

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:22.199
so I had to re-configure it.

00:08:22.199 --> 00:08:25.639
I then configured the G0/2 interface.

00:08:25.639 --> 00:08:32.890
Note that this time it worked, I was able
to configure G0/2 as 192.168.1.1/30 even though

00:08:32.890 --> 00:08:34.990
it overlaps with G0/0.

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:39.220
That’s because they are in separate VRFs.

00:08:39.220 --> 00:08:42.149
I then configured G0/3 as well.

00:08:42.149 --> 00:08:48.320
I then once again confirmed the VRFs and now
you can see the interfaces listed in the output.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:55.381
So, SPR1 is now divided into two separate
virtual routers: the CUSTOMER1 VRF, which

00:08:55.381 --> 00:09:03.240
includes G0/0 and G0/1, and the CUSTOMER2
VRF, which includes G0/2 and G0/3.

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:11.450
So, basic configuration of VRF-lite is simple:
create VRFs with the IP VRF command, and then

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:16.860
assign interfaces to VRFs with the IP VRF
FORWARDING command.

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:23.200
There is of course a lot more depth to VRFs,
but that’s all we’ll look at for now.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:28.450
I then used SHOW IP ROUTE on SPR1, but I don’t
see any routes.

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:32.959
Usually you’d expect to see connected and
local routes after configuring IP addresses

00:09:32.959 --> 00:09:37.640
on interfaces, so why is nothing displayed
here?

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:42.191
SHOW IP ROUTE displays the ‘global routing
table’, that’s the normal routing table

00:09:42.191 --> 00:09:45.350
you’re used to when not using VRFs.

00:09:45.350 --> 00:09:52.010
In this case, all of SPR1’s interfaces are
configured in VRFs, so nothing displays here.

00:09:52.010 --> 00:09:57.279
By the way, you can have a mix of interfaces
using and not using VRFs.

00:09:57.279 --> 00:10:04.959
So, I then used the command SHOW IP ROUTE
VRF CUSTOMER1, and now we can see some routes,

00:10:04.959 --> 00:10:08.589
the connected and local routes for G0/0 and
G0/1.

00:10:08.589 --> 00:10:14.900
So, if you want to see a VRF’s routing table
you have to add VRF and the VRF’s name to

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:16.970
the end of the command.

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:20.190
Here I viewed the CUSTOMER2 VRF’s routing
table.

00:10:20.190 --> 00:10:25.970
So, these are separate routing tables from
each other and from the global routing table.

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:30.649
By the way, if an interface is not in a VRF
its routes will appear in the global routing

00:10:30.649 --> 00:10:36.279
table, and it will be isolated from the interfaces
in VRFs, just like interfaces in different

00:10:36.279 --> 00:10:40.420
VRFs are isolated from each other.

00:10:40.420 --> 00:10:44.170
To test reachability, I tried some pings from
SPR1.

00:10:44.170 --> 00:10:50.130
I first pinged 192.168.1.2, but all the pings
failed.

00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:51.130
Why is that?

00:10:51.130 --> 00:10:55.300
It’s because, in the global routing table,
there are no routes.

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:59.860
As I showed in the previous slide, the global
routing table is empty.

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:06.130
You can specify the VRF when pinging like
this, PING VRF, the VRF name, and then the

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:07.550
destination.

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:09.720
This time the pings worked.

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:13.420
Which device was SPR1 pinging in this case?

00:11:13.420 --> 00:11:22.150
There are two devices with the IP address
192.168.1.2; C1R1 and C2R1, but in this case

00:11:22.150 --> 00:11:29.140
SPR1 was pinging C1R1 because I specified
the CUSTOMER1 VRF.

00:11:29.140 --> 00:11:38.580
In the CUSTOMER1 VRF again I pinged 192.168.11.2,
C1R2, which worked, and then 192.168.12.2,

00:11:38.580 --> 00:11:41.529
C2R2, which didn’t work.

00:11:41.529 --> 00:11:47.160
That’s because, in the CUSTOMER1 VRF’s
routing table, there is no route to the destination

00:11:47.160 --> 00:11:49.760
.12.2.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:55.769
This time I pinged 192.168.1.2 and specified
the CUSTOMER2 VRF.

00:11:55.769 --> 00:11:58.690
Who is SPR1 pinging this time?

00:11:58.690 --> 00:12:04.110
C2R1, connected to G0/2 in the CUSTOMER2 VRF.

00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:11.730
And I pinged 192.168.12.2, C2R2, which worked
this time because I pinged in the proper VRF.

00:12:11.730 --> 00:12:18.029
So, to sum it up, hosts in the same VRF can
communicate with each other, and hosts in

00:12:18.029 --> 00:12:20.310
different VRFs can’t.

00:12:20.310 --> 00:12:24.830
SPR1 was divided into two separate virtual
routers.

00:12:24.830 --> 00:12:28.149
Here’s what we covered in this video.

00:12:28.149 --> 00:12:34.260
I introduced VRFs and showed the basics of
how they are configured in Cisco IOS.

00:12:34.260 --> 00:12:39.459
But remember, what we mentioned in this video
is more accurately called ‘VRF-lite’,

00:12:39.459 --> 00:12:42.579
which means we’re not using VRF with MPLS.

00:12:42.579 --> 00:12:48.820
VRF is used to split a router up into multiple
virtual routers, each with their own routing

00:12:48.820 --> 00:12:50.630
table.

00:12:50.630 --> 00:12:56.279
Service providers can use VRFs to allow multiple
customers to connect to the same infrastructure

00:12:56.279 --> 00:12:59.050
while still allowing their traffic to be isolated.

00:12:59.050 --> 00:13:04.279
Plus, it doesn’t matter if customers use
the same IP addresses in their networks, because

00:13:04.279 --> 00:13:08.200
each VRF is a separate routing table.

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:13.779
For the CCNA, it’s enough to just understand
the basic purpose of VRF, but if you go further

00:13:13.779 --> 00:13:19.329
to study at the CCNP level and beyond you’ll
definitely have to study VRF in more depth.

00:13:19.329 --> 00:13:24.860
Okay, let’s go to the quiz, here’s question
1.

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:29.090
You issue the following commands on R1’s
G0/0 interface.

00:13:29.090 --> 00:13:36.899
However, after issuing show ip interface brief
you notice that G0/0 does not have an IP address.

00:13:36.899 --> 00:13:38.130
Why is that?

00:13:38.130 --> 00:13:42.200
Pause the video now to think about the answer.

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:50.950
Okay, the answer is B, the IP address was
removed by the IP VRF FORWARDING VRF1 command.

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:57.079
As I showed earlier, if an interface already
has an IP address, that IP address will be

00:13:57.079 --> 00:14:00.150
removed when you assign it to a VRF.

00:14:00.150 --> 00:14:03.139
You will then have to re-configure the IP
address.

00:14:03.139 --> 00:14:08.759
So, if you’re planning to use VRFs you should
configure the interface IP addresses after

00:14:08.759 --> 00:14:10.290
assigning them to VRFs.

00:14:10.290 --> 00:14:14.860
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:16.820
Examine the network below.

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:23.680
If you issue the command ping 192.168.1.10
on R1, which device will respond?

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:28.589
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:14:28.589 --> 00:14:33.930
Okay, the answer is D, no device will respond.

00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:38.310
Actually, R1 won’t be able to even send
the pings.

00:14:38.310 --> 00:14:44.300
All of R1’s interfaces are assigned to VRFs,
and a ping without specifying a VRF will use

00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:46.670
the global routing table.

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:51.269
None of R1’s interfaces are using the global
routing instance, so the routing table will

00:14:51.269 --> 00:14:53.890
be empty and it won’t be able to send the
pings.

00:14:53.890 --> 00:14:59.290
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:14:59.290 --> 00:15:04.650
Which of the following statements about VLANs
and VRFs are true? (select three).

00:15:04.650 --> 00:15:09.250
Pause the video now to select your answers.

00:15:09.250 --> 00:15:18.550
Okay, the answers are C, D, and F. VRFs divide
routers up by creating separate routing tables.

00:15:18.550 --> 00:15:23.410
In effect, you are dividing the router into
separate virtual routers.

00:15:23.410 --> 00:15:29.350
VLANs, on the other hand, divide switches
up by creating separate broadcast domains.

00:15:29.350 --> 00:15:34.070
And router interfaces in different VRFs can
have the same IP address, as I demonstrated

00:15:34.070 --> 00:15:36.149
in this video.

00:15:36.149 --> 00:15:41.639
A is incorrect because VRFs do not create
separate broadcast domains.

00:15:41.639 --> 00:15:47.300
Router interfaces are already in separate
broadcast domains anyway, without VRFs.

00:15:47.300 --> 00:15:52.660
B is wrong because VLANs do not create separate
MAC address tables, even when using VLANs

00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:56.470
the switch still keeps one MAC address table.

00:15:56.470 --> 00:16:01.980
And E is wrong because VRFs can also be configured
on the SVIs and routed ports of multilayer

00:16:01.980 --> 00:16:04.769
switches, not just on routers.

00:16:04.769 --> 00:16:07.589
Okay, that’s all for the quiz and this video.

00:16:07.589 --> 00:16:11.720
I hope it was helpful, thanks for watching.

